hildren","fullItemName":"Scenario: Delayed walking in children"},{"id":"f63a11de-e155-5afe-a226-402d885f4423","slug":"limp-in-children","fullItemName":"Scenario: Limp in children"},{"id":"da28c3e0-278d-5fce-8968-bdc734d3e305","slug":"out-toeing","fullItemName":"Scenario: Out-toeing"},{"id":"3130a07e-303c-5b73-838c-5d6307fdead8","slug":"tip-toe-walking","fullItemName":"Scenario: Tip toe walking"}]},{"id":"086fd10d-b722-534e-b18d-5a0a2d5792c9","fullItemName":"Supporting evidence","slug":"supporting-evidence","subChapters":[]},{"id":"bf424233-1954-55a8-98de-834693dbdd11","fullItemName":"How this topic was developed","slug":"how-this-topic-was-developed","subChapters":[{"id":"6728c56f-47a6-56f1-be0e-22c22275d9e9","slug":"search-strategy","fullItemName":"Search strategy"},{"id":"2d75ec25-86dd-542a-b968-a3f7e80d0210","slug":"stakeholder-engagement","fullItemName":"Stakeholder engagement"},{"id":"2514c9ed-51af-51be-8f7d-3a997605efe6","slug":"evidence-exclusion-criteria","fullItemName":"Evidence exclusion criteria"},{"id":"6bdf3ba0-4bec-595d-bb71-c68f7fcb7c9c","slug":"organizational-behavioural-financial-barriers","fullItemName":"Organizational, behavioural and financial barriers"},{"id":"20bd862c-7ca7-5a5b-8f5d-443cd0bea04c","slug":"declarations-of-interest","fullItemName":"Declarations of interest"}]},{"id":"b747cefd-4366-540b-87c3-72fdbb926a30","fullItemName":"References","slug":"references","subChapters":[]}]},"parentChapter":{"id":"8d402bd6-6ff7-597f-8744-fe50598828b1","slug":"management","fullItemName":"Management"},"subChapters":[{"id":"ddc213ee-8d92-5e8d-8f61-36f79ae21d4e","slug":"back-pain","fullItemName":"Back pain","depth":3,"htmlHeader":"","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 61c110f0-38b7-476b-a981-aa0d00e73cd9 --><!-- begin field 2d9f8ec2-a6da-45b8-883b-aa0d00e73cd9 -->When should I consider referring a child with back pain?<!-- end field 2d9f8ec2-a6da-45b8-883b-aa0d00e73cd9 --><!-- begin field 5bb155b9-76ae-4b41-8d9e-aa0d00e73cd9 --><ul><li><strong>Management in the community (for example by a physiotherapist with paediatric expertise) is usually appropriate for a child with back pain if <em>all</em> of the following are present: </strong><ul><li>The child is well with no <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/diagnosis/assessment-for-red-flags/\">red flags</a>.</li><li>There are no neurological symptoms.</li><li>Examination is normal.</li><li>There is no functional impairment (for example, walking, playing).</li></ul></li><li><strong>Consider referring children with back pain for specialist assessment, using clinical judgement to determine the urgency, if <em>any</em> of the following are present: </strong><ul><li><a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/diagnosis/assessment-for-red-flags/\">Red flag</a> features (urgent referral to paediatrics, paediatric rheumatology, or paediatric orthopaedics).</li><li>Pain:<ul><li>Occurs at night or wakes them from sleep. </li><li>Is constant and unremitting (even when supine).</li><li>Spreads into the buttocks or legs. </li><li>Is sudden onset and severe.<strong> </strong></li><li>Lasts for more than 2 weeks and is worsening. </li><li>Is widespread, not just affecting the back. </li><li>Is focal or affects the cervical or thoracic spine. </li></ul></li><li>Any of the following symptoms or signs are present:<ul><li>Systemic symptoms, for example fever, chills, significant unexplained weight loss, night sweats. </li><li>Neurological features on history or examination (such as limb weakness, sensory loss, neuropathic pain, headaches). </li><li>Bowel/bladder dysfunction or saddle anaesthesia. </li><li>Limp (intermittent or persistent) or gait changes. </li><li>Joint symptoms elsewhere.<strong> </strong></li><li>Stiffness with inactivity or rest, or in the morning for more than 30 minutes. </li><li>Vertebral or localised spinal tenderness (including sacroiliac joints) or deformity (such as scoliosis) are detected on examination.<strong> </strong></li><li>Changes in behaviour in very young children, such as distress or general irritability.</li><li>Functional impairment, including absence from school.</li></ul></li><li>The child has a history of:<ul><li>Juvenile idiopathic arthritis or inflammatory bowel disease. </li><li>Scoliosis or osteoporosis.</li><li>Immunocompromise or HIV infection. </li><li>Previous malignancy. </li><li>Corticosteroid use.<strong> </strong></li><li>Recent trauma.</li><li>Sickle cell disease.</li><li>Tuberculosis.<strong> </strong></li><li>Multiple presentations with the same problem but no clear diagnosis.<strong> </strong></li></ul></li><li>There is a family history of orthopaedic, neurological, rheumatic, or HLA B27-associated diseases (for example psoriasis, inflammatory bowel disease, reactive arthritis, and ankylosing spondylitis). </li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 5bb155b9-76ae-4b41-8d9e-aa0d00e73cd9 --><!-- end item 61c110f0-38b7-476b-a981-aa0d00e73cd9 -->","subChapters":[{"id":"7c2e9553-46c9-54cd-a365-ff0c382e615f","slug":"basis-for-recommendation-f00","fullItemName":"Basis for recommendation","depth":4,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 303fc093-ea59-45c0-820f-aa0d00e73cdb --><h4>Basis for recommendation</h4><!-- end field 303fc093-ea59-45c0-820f-aa0d00e73cdb -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item f00bde9d-4a71-42a1-8e15-aa0d00e73cdb --><!-- begin field 6746f541-6c93-44a3-b5ac-aa0d00e73cdb --><h4>Community management</h4><ul><li>The recommendation on when community management is usually appropriate is based on musculoskeletal triage guidance for children and young people [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">RightPath, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">RightPath, 2019</a>].  </li></ul><h4>Referral</h4><ul><li>The recommendation on when to consider referral is based on musculoskeletal triage guidance for children and young people [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">RightPath, 2017</a>]<strong>,</strong> expert opinion in review articles [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Cruikshank and Ramanan, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Jakes, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">MacDonald et al, 2017</a>], and expert opinion from a reviewer of this CKS topic.  <ul><li>Features such as night pain, constant pain, or radiation into the buttocks or legs may indicate an underlying diagnosis such as infection, arthritis, fracture, or malignancy [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Jakes, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">MacDonald et al, 2017</a>].</li><li>Widespread pain may be indicative of a chronic pain syndrome [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Cruikshank and Ramanan, 2014</a>].   </li><li>Likewise, the presence of systemic symptoms can also suggest potentially serious causes of back pain, including infection, tuberculosis, or malignancy (for example lymphoma) [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Jakes, 2015</a>]. </li><li>Neurological features may be a sign of nerve or spinal cord compression, with bladder and bowel dysfunction suggestive of cauda equina compression [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Jakes, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">MacDonald et al, 2017</a>]. </li><li>Morning stiffness is indicative of an inflammatory cause, particularly if there is associated uveitis or enthesitis. Experts suggest there is a need to investigate for juvenile arthritis and ankylosing spondylitis in this situation [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Cruikshank and Ramanan, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Jakes, 2015</a>].  </li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 6746f541-6c93-44a3-b5ac-aa0d00e73cdb --><!-- end item f00bde9d-4a71-42a1-8e15-aa0d00e73cdb -->","subChapters":[]}]}]}}},"staticQueryHashes":["3666801979"]}